'''Muhammad Paolo Zaman Kirmani''' known as '''Muhammad Zaman''' ([[Floruit|fl.]] 1680 – c. 1700), a famous [[Safavid]] [[Persian calligraphy|calligrapher]] and [[Persian painting|painter]].

==Life==
He was a native of [[Kirman]], [[Greater Persia|Persia]]. He received his education in [[Tabriz]]. He was sent to [[Rome]] under the reign of [[Shah Abbas II]]. He returned to Persia as a [[Catholic]] [[Christians|Christian]] with the name Paolo.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3AYkAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA256&lpg=PA256&dq=muhammad+zaman+catholic&source=bl&ots=U0kMgblu0F&sig=7iQ-bW7C6-9BZ1uYaHIJFqW3Gv4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj706aqjJDOAhVDUZAKHTSXCD4Q6AEIJTAC#v=onepage&q=muhammad%20zaman%20catholic&f=false books.google.com.br]</ref> Because of his conversion to Roman Catholicism he was obliged to escape from Persia to [[India]] where he obtained the protection of the [[Moghul dynasty]].

[[File:Shahnama (Book of Kings) Abu'l Qasim Firdausi (935–1020).jpg|thumb|A [[Persian miniature]] by Muhammad Zaman. The landscape in the background shows European painting influences.]]
Muhammad Zaman was influenced by [[Italian Renaissance painting|Italian painting]] techniques. However, as Ivanov suggests, Muhammad Zaman studied under a European artist in [[Isfahan]], Persia, and the report of his being sent by Shah Abbas II to study in Italy, where he adopted Roman Catholic Christianity, is no more than a colourful legend.<ref>''History of Civilizations of Central Asia: Development in contrast : from the sixteenth to the mid-nineteenth'' by Chahryar Adle, Irfan Habib</ref>

It is reported{{By whom|date=June 2014}} that [[Niccolao Manucci|Manucci]] the famous traveller made the acquaintance of Muhammad Zaman at the court of [[Aurangzib]].

