'''Hamza''' ({{lang-ar|همزة}}, ''{{transl|ar|ALA|hamzah}}'') ({{lang|ar|[[wikt:ء|ء]]}}) is a letter in the [[Arabic alphabet]], representing the [[glottal stop]] {{IPAblink|ʔ}}. Hamza is not one of the 28 "full" letters and owes its existence to historical inconsistencies in the [[orthography|standard writing system]]. It is derived from the Arabic letter ''[[Ayin|ʿAyn]]''. In the [[Phoenician alphabet|Phoenician]] and [[Aramaic alphabet|Aramaic]] alphabets, from which the Arabic alphabet is descended, the glottal stop was expressed by ''[[aleph|alif]]'' ([[File:Phoenician aleph.svg|15px]]), continued by ''Alif'' (&nbsp;[[File:Alif-individua-cropt.svg|2px]]&nbsp;) in the Arabic alphabet. However, Alif was used to express both a glottal stop and also a long vowel {{IPA|/aː/}}. In order to indicate that a glottal stop is used, and not a mere vowel, it was added to Alif [[diacritic]]ally. In modern orthography,  hamza may also appear on the line, under certain circumstances as though it were a full letter, independent of an Alif. In [[Unicode]] it is at the code point U+0621 and named {{sc|ARABIC LETTER HAMZA}}.

== Etymology ==
''Hamza'' is derived from the verb ''{{transl|ar|ALA|hamaza}}'' ({{lang-ar|هَمَزَ}}) meaning ‘to prick, goad, drive’ or ‘to provide (a letter or word) with hamzah’.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wehr|first= Hans|editor-last= Cowan|editor-first= J. M.|title= The Hans Wehr Dictionary of Modern Arabic|publisher= Otto Harrassowitz KG|year= 1994|chapter= همز ''hamaza''|isbn=978-0-87950-003-0|edition=4th}}</ref>

== Hamzat al-waṣl ==
{{see also|Arabic definite article|sun and moon letters}}

The letter Hamza on its own always represents ''{{transl|ar|ALA|hamzat qaṭ‘}}'' ({{lang-ar|هَمْزَة الْقَطْع|links=no}}); that is, a phonemic glottal stop unlike the ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Hamzat al-Waṣl|}}'' ({{lang-ar|هَمْزَة الْوَصْل|links=no}}), a non-phonemic glottal stop produced automatically at the beginning of an utterance. Although it can be written as [[aleph|Alif]] carrying a ''{{transl|ar|ALA|[[wasla|Waṣlah]]}}'' sign {{lang|ar|ٱ}} (notably in the [[Quran]]), it is normally indicated by a plain Alif without a Hamza.

It occurs in:

* the definite article ''{{transl|ar|ALA|[[al-]]}}''
* some short words with two-consonant roots like ''{{transl|ar|ALA|ism, ibn, ibna, imr, imra, ithnāni, ithnatāni}}''
* the imperative verbs of forms I and VII to X
* the perfective aspect of verb forms VII to X and their verbal nouns
* some borrowed words that start with consonant clusters such as ''{{transl|ar|ALA|istūdiyū}}''

It is not pronounced following a vowel: (''{{transl|ar|ALA|al-baytu l-kabīru}}'' for written {{lang|ar|البيت الكبير}}). It occurs only in the [[definite article]] or at the beginning of a word following a [[preposition]].

